Outstanding menu options. My entire family enjoyed it. We received exceptional customer service. They mixed fruit juice drinks for my kids. During one meal, my daughter ordered fresh fruit. Our server told her he knew something that would really make it taste good and brought her back a cup of whipped cream. She was more than happy. The salads were awesome. Evening happy hour specials were great. Great synergy among the staff. The host was always nice and checked on us in addition to the server. You can view the kitchen and chefs cooking which was cool. We’re staying at the Marriott. The kids wanted to try other food however the last two days chose Fire and Sage for each meal.
Delicious

We had drinks and appetizers here on two different nights during our stay. The first night it was a quiet weeknight and everything was great. Drinks and food were top notch. The second night (on a weekend), however was not good at all. Our friend ordered a bourbon on the rocks and the waitress brought out the drink in a glass filled with ice as if it were a soda (the other night it was brought out with a single sphere of ice). My wife ordered a dessert and it was obviously microwaved since some parts were hot and some parts were still frozen. I'm guessing that the restaurant lacks consistency when it is busy.

Nice quiet spot for happy hour or to grab some lunch/dinner. Scrumptious battered fries and decent home-made quinoa burger.  While I appreciate a house-made veggie burger loaded with quinoa, zucchini, peppers, and corn (thankfully the Impossible Burger hasn't swooped in!), it was a bit bland. The thick layer of melted pepperjack cheese coating the patty was over the top without adding any real flavor. Hold the cheese please. The toppings served on the side elevated the burger with pickled onions, pickles, tomato, and lettuce. The fully loaded burger was held in place by the toothpick!  While the quinoa burger was satisfying, the crispy battered fries really sealed the meal! Not a fry was spared. Would be nice if the quinoa burger was offered as part of the $12 lunch deal.  Will have to try the stone-oven flatbreads on happy hour next time along with some fries!
The service is absolutely perfect and the food was amazing!

Came for Happy hour and got one $5 drink. For the next four days there was a hold on my account for $50! When I called to inquire, the manager told me, in a condescending tone, that it’s a standard restaurant practice and it depends on your bank. I work in the restaurant industry and know many others who do. It’s not normal. At least put up some sort of sign to notify those who would rather just pay cash. Drink: 3/5 All human interaction: 1/5

I had my doubts about a 17 dollar Reubin, and a 32 dollar Scallop dinner, but they were well worth the exorbitant Washington DC price.  The scallops were large and seared to perfection, and the potatoes and spinach blended perfectly with the  bacon garnish. Really a good dinner - much better than I expected at a hotel restaurant.

Revising my review...  Okay, so, my first night I ate here, I got a generic burger. You know, in a rush, not having time to look at a menu, so you go with an old standby. It wasn't bad, but not impressive either. Tonight, I tried their Ruben. Then I vowed to plant my oversized behind in this stool until the end of time and eat the same thing until death came knocking. It's a perfect heap of pastrami coupled with a spicy remoulade and mild sauerkraut on toasted rye bread and although it sounds simple, I can't get over the perfect combination. This was perfect and goes down as one of my top ten places for a great evening classic. If you're looking for a meal to be unapologetically messy over, come get a Ruben in their crafty, gastro-pub-like atmosphere.

Every time I go to this restaurant in the Metrocenter Marriott, they treat me like a VIP. Waiters, doormen, hostesses - and once a chef- stop by and talk to me like an old friend. It's reasonably priced and everything on the menu is served and delicious (except the salads and the drinks which are the appropriate temp lol.)  Booths are roomy, you can come in at lunch snd eat alone or with friends. The drinks are consistent too, try the martinis. Also a great place for an after work drink, to meet and eat before going to a second location.

(Translated by Google) The food is quite good and the atmosphere is quite elegant. In fact, it seems like a good place for a business lunch, and they even have a lounge area reserved for meals of this kind or birthday. In my case, I celebrated a friend's birthday, (how much it costs to turn years once I don't enter the thirties!). The service was regular as long as it took a long time to ask for the note, although I will not say that it was bad just for that. In short, it's not bad. Value for money good.  (Original) La comida está bastante buena y el ambiente es bastante elegante. De hecho, me parece un buen lugar para una comida de negocios, e incluso tienen una zona de la sala reservada para comidas de esta índole o cumpleaños. En mi caso, celebré el cumpleaños de una amiga, (¡cuánto cuesta cumplir años una vez que no entre en la treintena!). El servicio fue regular en tanto en cuanto tardaron bastante rato en pedir la nota, aunque tampoco voy a decir que fué malo sólo por eso. En resumidas cuentas, no está mal. I was staying at Marriott for a conference and had a drink and dessert at fire and sage.  The waitress was completely unattentive and when she brought my check, she didn't even bring me a pen to sign the bill, so she got the tip she deserved....nothing.  Surprise to me that when I look at my statement she has given herself a 40% tip.  I called the manager, Anthony Stuart, who promised on three separate occasions to fix the problem, including, on his own will, offering to refund the whole amount.  Three weeks have passed and nothing.  Not the sign of a quality eating establishment.
Small booths, average service and pricey salads but it's a quiet spot for a business lunch.
